#1 pho in the city. Best tasting and oh so  FLAVORFUL broth. Usually get the beef special, but honestly EVERYTHING IS GOOD HERE including their iced coffee!!! The pho here is decent, but it annoys me that they never give you enough broth. The broth to noodle/beef/vegetables ratio is very important for pho, but here, I find myself always having to scrounge to get enough broth, especially as I get towards the end. If you go to most other pho restaurants, when the bowl first comes out, you'll see that the broth almost completely covers the noodles. Here, the level of the broth usually sits below the top of the noodle, which is not enough. I'm not sure if this is true for takeout as well, since I always dine in here. This place at least deserves kudos for opening their restaurant for dine-in, unlike most other pho restaurants that are still only doing takeout, which in my opinion really takes away from the quality of the pho, regardless of the restaurant.

I was one of its first customer's.  Although small it has a bar and a number of tables. Family run it has a number of appetizers roles of various types. But the main course is a pho. For me great pho. A selection of meat and tendon combinations. I've tried them all. I usually start with a Vietnamese iced coffee. It comes with condensed milk in the bottom of a glass with an individual French style drip coffee on the top of the glass. You can watch it drip and then mix coffee milk and add ice. There are various other main dishes but I like the cat fish and rice. Just the smell of garlic is fantastic. It has a good selection of juices and smoothes. Service is quick. Atmosphere is family. Evenings can be full. If you sit at the right table you can watch TV. It has captions so it doesn't compete with conversation. Summer time you can sit outside on a patio. Prices are reasonable. Several side streets have parking some with meters. Provides a pleasant unhurried change of pace and a fresh taste.

This is the kind of phở that you have to be ready to take a pic of the second it arrives and post after you eat it. They quickly blanch their phở noodles first instead of just pouring the broth over raw noodles (the right way IMHO) which means the noodles aren't all clumped together and hard when you first get it. However, this also means that the noodles will get soggy MUCH faster the longer they sit in the broth. So you gotta eat FAST unless (you're into soggy noodles, no judgment).  Ordered my standard, the phở tái with rare beef, number 11 or 12. It came out a beautiful pink and tasted so tender. The broth was flavorful, a tad salty for me but came with all the necessary herbs and condiments.  TLDR: Eating a hot bowl of phở outside on a humid summer day reminded me of phở in the motherland. It's a walk from the metro, but it's worth it. Even in the summer.

First, we get there and the server asked us what we wanted to eat before seating us, asking for drinks, anything. Next, the server explained what was on the menu and I asked her to please slow down because I couldn’t understand her accent. She followed my question with talking even faster, but with a frustrated attitude. Next, she blatantly stared at my date and I with a dirty look for so long that I had to ask if there was a problem, to which she just smiled and looked away without responding. Lastly, after making my meal uncomfortable from the blatant disrespect, I asked the waitress for a container so I could take my meal home and for the check. In the MIDDLE of me talking, she turned to someone else and started speaking Spanish and laughing, knowing I wouldn’t understand. I had to get the attention of another server to get my check.  If you’re looking for slightly above average food and terrible service, I 10/10 recommend this restaurant. I will never return to this restaurant.

A few veggies in pho. I guess it could satisfy some pho cravings, but there are a lot better places nearby.  May 2018: This now tops my list as one of the best pho places in the District. The place is small (even with the outdoor seating), so there may be a wait. But the service is efficient and the food comes out quickly. Their menu has other options, including vermicelli rice bowls.

I will NEVER step foot in this establishment again.  I left my debit card at home, but I keep a picture of it on my phone. When I arrived, I explained this to one of the waitresses and recognizing me as a regular customer, she was totally fine with it.  I waited for my food for about 10-15 min.  Another waitress brought my food when it was ready, and  asked Lina how to manually input the credit card info.  Lina immediately dismissed me saying she can’t take the card and could not serve me.  She was walking and looking away when I tried to talk to her and barely even acknowledged my presence.  I’ve seen her treat people like this before, but never thought I would be one of them, particularly since I was such a frequent patron.  Lina then went on a long rant saying that she couldn’t manually input the card because “you people” might dispute the charge (insinuating that I would do that).  Question: Who is “you people”? 🤔 She then asked the waitresses if they told me that they would manually input the card info.  The staff, of course, lied and said they didn’t tell me they would manually input the info.  But I can’t even blame them, they wanted to keep their jobs.  She runs the restaurant like a plantation, so the employees are horrified of her.  At any rate, had I known she wouldn’t accept the card manually, I could’ve simply went home and got my card while they were preparing my food.  I live 5 minutes away.  Long story short, what hurt me the most is that (1) my months of patronage was not appreciated or acknowledged and (2) I guarantee that Lina would not have treated any white woman the way she treated me.  I feel humiliated, embarrassed, belittled, and all of the various words you can think of.  I will never stop foot in this establishment again.  Lina is a mean person, and she will reap everything she sows.  I will also be reporting this place to the BBB, DC Consumer Affairs, and any other entity that I can find.  BTW - After discussing this with friends who live in the area, I learned that they have a mice, which is even more reason for me to never step foot in this place again.
